&lt;p&gt;We are looking to recruit a committed Speech and Language Therapist who has enthusiasm and compassion for supporting and enabling young people with complex needs with a particular interest in youth forensic services. We invite you to join our well established health care team within a Local Authority provision. The team is comprised of a Forensic Psychologist, two Mental Health Nurses, an Occupational Therapist, a Substance Misuse Nurse and Physical Health care Nurse. We are looking to recruit a committed Speech and Language Therapist who has enthusiasm and compassion for supporting and enabling young people with complex needs with a particular interest in youth forensic services. We invite you to join our well established health care team within a Local Authority provision. The team is comprised of a Forensic Psychologist, two Mental Health Nurses, an Occupational Therapist, a Substance Misuse Nurse and Physical Health care Nurse. We have direct business support from two Administrators and support from a Child &amp; Adolescent Consultant Psychiatrist.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Lincolnshire secure unit is a 12 bedded secure children’s home, housing those serving youth custodial sentences or residing under a court welfare order. We work within the Secure Stairs model of care. The model involves training staff to provide more psychologically informed trauma responsive care surrounding comprehensive, co-produced assessments to ensure all needs are identified and addressed. The health care staff provide a team approach to all of the Young people including close collaboration and consultation to the care and education staff on site.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The successful applicant will work with adolescents, their families/carers and wider community care teams providing appropriate assessment and intervention. This post will involve participation in multi-disciplinary team meetings and occasionally supporting the delivery of training to the care team.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will have an understanding of the communication needs for young people with a multitude of complex difficulties such as attachment disorder and Autistic spectrum disorder. You must be able to demonstrate this with recent and on-going clinical professional development.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The successful candidate can expect to work within a friendly, professional and passionate team, receive regular managerial and clinical supervision, an annual appraisal and training opportunities.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In addition to other attractive benefits from LPFT there is the availability of a £4,000 payment in lieu of relocation (to assist with commuting) or full relocation package.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
